<subSubSection id="D101B4AC3A3550B43B8CC0EBE3AD58C7" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="7226FE51FD63C2096E49C6038F0A1CEE" pageNumber="153">
Etymology L 
<taxonomicName id="0B4EFA2D0EF893085705F0BCF183116C" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33716" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole diversipilosa Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole diversipilosa Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diversipilosa">diversipilosa</taxonomicName>
, different (variable) hair, alluding to the major.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="06989DBF096017E5D42D5150F4AE9D0B" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="CA38373CD6A0B5638974A8ABEA087223" pageNumber="153">
diagnosis Very close to 
<taxonomicName id="66E84A880D17BA50D781E5794322B73C" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33688" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole crassicornis Emery" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole crassicornis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassicornis">crassicornis</taxonomicName>
from which it differs in the major by abundant pilosity on the mesosoma and gaster, and 
<taxonomicName id="FF17DE914D4CCBA260E73A18E74CF2E6" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181655" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole tetra Creighton" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole tetra Creighton" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tetra">tetra</taxonomicName>
, from which it differs in the major by the much shorter pilosity on the first gastral tergite and by sparseness or absence of pilosity on the waist and occiput.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9FE41C13E9C1D43AF55BCC678FC8CBA9" pageNumber="153">
Also resembles 
<taxonomicName id="84D45EBB61C1A94AFC2E407FD37CED1E" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181652" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole pilosior Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole pilosior Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosior">pilosior</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="FF5419B0783AD45DB7169F4CCB32A32B" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33938" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole porcula Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole porcula Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="porcula">porcula</taxonomicName>
in various traits as depicted.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7AFB3082EF993407F6275A12774FFC62" type="description">
<paragraph id="578FA57833AB643716276BC6501A8489" pageNumber="153">Measurements (mm) Lectotype major: HW 1.26, HL 1.34, SL 0.66, EL 0.20, PW 0.66. Paralectotype minor: HW 0.66, HL 0.74, SL 0.76, EL 0.16, PW 0.46. color Major and minor: body medium reddish brown, appendages light reddish brown. Range Southwestern Texas to the mountains of southern and central Arizona.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="91CFBE487A7C1F2D6212D960A97BE83D" pageNumber="153">
Biology According to Stefan Cover (personal communication), 
<taxonomicName id="740700302542081330EF11FED34E12C0" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33716" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole diversipilosa Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole diversipilosa Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diversipilosa">diversipilosa</taxonomicName>
is common at mid-elevations (1050-1900 m), favoring oak-pine-juniper forests, especially those in creek valleys, where it nests under rocks and in open soil. Colonies have single queens and large populations, which can exceed 1000 workers. Seed caches have been found in some nests.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
